    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-05-31T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-05-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="308"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d308">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.945/1123: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Woods</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-05-31T14:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 31, 1924—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 31—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>130. Due to the attitude of the Government as set forth in the last paragraph of
                    my 125, May 28, 4 p.m., there have been no popular anti-American outbreaks but
                    this does not signify that there has been any lessening of deep-seated
                    resentment and bitterness throughout Japan. The nation can be considered to be
                    behind the Government in any protest they may make at Washington and it would
                        <pb facs="0497" n="403" xml:id="pg_403"/> be a mistake to interpret their
                    protest as actuated by mainly domestic political urgency.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Woods</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
